context: The first actual usage of the term prime minister or <b4_0>Premier Ministre<b4_0/>[citation needed] was used by <a1_0><b5_0><b6_0>Cardinal Richelieu<b6_0/><b5_0/><a1_0/> when in <a0_0>1625<a0_0/> he was named to head the royal council as prime minister of <a2_0>France<a2_0/>. <a3_0><b7_0>Louis XIV<a3_0/> and his descendants<b7_0/> generally attempted to avoid giving this title to their chief ministers.
